'''Charles Wesley Powell''' (05 May 1854 - 18 August 1927) was an American hobbyist turned horticulturist specializing in the study of orchids ([[Orchidaceae]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Charles Wesley|title=List of orchidologists|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_orchidologists|website=Wikipedia|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=employee>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Charles W.|title=United States, Panama Canal Sailing lists, 1905-1937|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-1961-40627-11784-79?cc=2193241|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> He is credited with providing scientists the first large-scale collection of orchid specimens found in [[Panama]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Richard|first1=Eunice|title=Orchids and orchidology in Central America|journal=Panama Canal Review|date=1974|issue=Special Edition|page=20|url=http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00097366/00172/19j|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> In the early 1900s, he became internationally famous for his new discoveries and valuable contributions to orchidology by gathering, ''rediscovering'', cultivating, preserving, documenting, and forwarding-for-study a diverse assortment of hundreds of distinct specimens: yielding many new to science [[species]].<ref name=union>{{cite journal|last1=Heald|first1=Jean|title=Panama, The home of the orchid|journal=Bulletin of the Pan American Union|date=January 1927|volume=61|pages=671-678|url=https://archive.org/details/bulletinofpaname6127pana|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>

Powell's specimen records (also known as herbarium specimens) and his Panama garden were studied by researchers at the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | Royal Botanical Gardens]], the Berlin Botanical Garden, Harvard University, the Smithsonian Institution, and the [[Missouri Botanical Garden]] (MBG). Dozens of orchid species were named in his honor.<ref name=lank /> In 1922, German botanist Rudolf Schlechter published his 95 page ''Orchidaceae Powellianae Panamenses'' (collections by C. Powell): principally on the basis of
Powell's efforts.<ref name=sch>{{cite book|last1=Schlechter|first1=Rudolf|title=Orchidaceae Powellianae Panamenses|date=1922|publisher=Verlag des Repertoriums|location=Germany}}</ref> Powell's work remains relevant not only because his records document valuable scientific data, but they continue to provide material for study &ndash; many of his digitized herbarium specimens are freely available online via [[Virtual herbarium | virtual herbaria]]. 

In 1926, Powell donated his world-class orchid garden (orchidarium) to the renowned MBG of St. Louis, Missouri.<ref name=expert>{{cite news|last1=Powell|first1=C. W.|title=C. W. Powell, Noted Orchid Expert, Dies in Panama|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/59846396/?terms=c.+w.+powell+orchid|accessdate=14 September 2014|publisher=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|date=August 19, 1927}}</ref><ref name=lank>{{cite journal|title=Orchids and orchidology in Central America|journal=Lankesteriana|date=August 2009|volume=9|issue=1-2|pages=358-378|url=http://ufdcimages.uflib.ufl.edu/UF/00/09/87/23/00023/00008-2009.pdf|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref> Under Powell's direction, a Tropical Station was created by the MBG in Balboa, Panama; 7,000 plants from Powell's orchid garden populated the satellite operation. For the MBG, a snowball effect occurred in the tropics; orchid collecting began there in earnest and over the next 13 years, orchids from its Tropical Station would appreciably augment the collection of the parent garden in St. Louis. "Today, the Missouri Botanical Garden<U+2019>s orchid collection represents one of the largest and finest in the United States."<ref>{{cite web|title=Orchids|url=http://www.missouribotanicalgarden.org/gardens-gardening/our-garden/notable-plant-collections/orchids.aspx|website=Missouri Botanical Garden.org|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref>
==Early life==
[[File: Charles Lesslie Pullen July 1854.1.jpg|thumb|Ben K. Pullen, 1854]]
Known to orchid enthusiasts as C. W. Powell, he was born '''Charles Lesslie Pullen''' in Richmond, Virginia, to Benjamin King Pullen Sr. and Minerva "Minnie" Anner ([[n<U+00E9>e]] Smith) Pullen.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pullin|first1=Chas. L.|title=Virginia, Births and Christenings, 1853-1917|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/X5KP-S2V|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=expert /> He was the first-born of eight children. In a letter to Minnie dated July 29,1854, from Richmond, Ben Pullen writes about his son: {{cquote|Darling little Lesslie [as called in childhood; as spelled by father]  I am so glad he is well and cries for his pa. Bless his pure little heart. '[[Hush, Little Baby |Hush my baby]] don't you cry Your papa will come by ner bye.'  I would walk a mile to see him this minute. Mrs Anderson + Letitia Rowe were in the store yesterday. They send <u>a heap</u> of love to you + Lesslie. [...] Affectionately Ben K. Pullen}}

In 1860, 6 year old Lesslie and his family moved, by train, {{convert|800|mile|km}} southwest to [[Memphis, Tennessee]], for the opening of his father's china store. Shortly thereafter, Lesslie was uprooted again when his family relocated {{convert|50|mile|km}} south for several years. There they struggled to survive on a cousin<U+2019>s farm near [[Sardis, Mississippi]], during the [[Union Army]]'s occupation of [[Battle of Memphis|Memphis]] in the [[American Civil War]] and Ben Pullen Sr.'s service as a [[Confederate Army]] officer.<ref name=bio /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pullen|first1=B K|title=United States Census, 1870|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/MD8Q-Z42|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>  Perhaps this experience was Lesslie's introduction to [[agriculture]].

==Family life, bookkeeper, book-lover, genealogist==
;1870s
After the War, the Pullens moved back to Memphis. In 1871, hard times in the South forced Lesslie<U+2019>s father to advertise his store's closing. By the mid-1870s, Ben Pullen Sr. was a bookkeeper for the State National Bank and Lesslie, now calling himself Charles, was a collector for the bank.

In 1877 he married Adelaide "Addie" Belle Prince (1858-1901), the daughter of a [[Mississippi]] antebellum cotton planter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Addie Belle Pullen|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=103459437&ref=acom|website=findagrave.com|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> In 1879, the couple's first child, Charles Lesslie was born (living only a few months). Six more children would follow: Bessie, an unnamed infant,<ref>{{cite web|title=infant Pullen|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Pullen&GSiman=1&GScid=11738&GRid=103459594&|website=findagrave.com|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> David (died young),<ref>{{cite web|title=David Hadden Pullen|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=103459757|website=findagrave|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> Adelaide "Addie", Minerva "Minnie", and Margaret. Bessie was born in 1880, and the couple's latter three daughters were born in 1887, 1891, and 1898 respectively.

The [[History of yellow fever#Lower Mississippi Valley: 1878|Yellow Fever]] Epidemic hit Memphis in 1878 claiming, among thousands, the life of Pullen<U+2019>s mother.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Keating|first1=John McLeod|title=A History of the Yellow Fever: The Yellow Fever Epidemic of 1878, in Memphis|date=1879|publisher=Wrightson & CO.|location=Cincinnati, Ohio|page=194, 240|edition=1|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ZQMW-S0MRjkC&q=pullen#v=snippet&q=pullen&f=false|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>
;1880s
In the early 1880s, Pullen was appointed to serve Memphis in several leadership positions. Detail oriented, well-read, and popular, he served as Secretary of the Legislative Council of Memphis; Secretary of the Fire and Police Commissioners Board; and Clerk for the Supervisors of Public Works, earning $100 per month. Documenting the day-to-day business of a struggling city, he proved valuable to the citizens who put him in office.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pullen|first1=Chas L.|title=Digest of the Acts Repealing the Charters of Certain Municipal Corporations|date=1898|publisher=S. C. Toof & Company|location=Memphis, TN|pages=76, 81, 105, 114, 158, 229,|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=5mBCAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA81&lpg=RA1-PA81&dq=chas+l+pullen+memphis&source=bl&ots=vrVlShgY5B&sig=GbvZJzQCz3knvIW-gNzB7l54SS4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Bm0QVOL4DYWHyAT4vIBo&ved=0CDEQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=chas%20l%20pullen%20memphis&f=false|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> "Memphis began to recover quickly after [the Yellow Fever Epidemic of] 1878. Its artesian water supply was discovered and turned into one of the purest water supplies in the nation in the 1880s. Its charter was restored. Its sanitation and sewer systems became models for other cities."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lollar|first1=Michael|title=Yellow fever left mark on Memphis|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/local-news/yellow-fever-left-mark-on-memphis|accessdate=14 September 2014|publisher=The Commercial Appeal|date=September 11, 2010}}</ref> In 1885 he bought part-interest in a weekly paper ''The Sunday Times'' and was its business manager. He was not only a bookkeeper, but also a book-lover; Pullen collected rare books. His interests went beyond the literary world, however. He conducted exhaustive research on his Pullen and Smith [[genealogy]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pullen|first1=Charles L|title=Dedham Historical Register, Volume 2|date=1891|publisher=Dedham Historical Society|location=Dedham, MA|pages=40, 82|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=z4slAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA40&lpg=PA40&dq=chas+l+pullen+memphis&source=bl&ots=Ns4EnpRD05&sig=u88PZu5E_zqv_83WqpQBAcjTt5c&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Bm0QVOL4DYWHyAT4vIBo&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=chas%20l%20pullen%20memphis&f=false|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Relentless in his pursuit of ancestral names and important dates, he advertised for information throughout [[New England]].
{{Quote box
|quote ='''Notice to Town Clerks''' If every Town Clerk in the New England States who sees this notice, will examine the town Records of Births, Deaths, and Marriages, and will send me a copy therefrom of every entry of a Pullen birth, death or marriage, he may find; I will remit his fee bill for making copy, on receipt of same. Memphis, Tenn. Chas. L. Pullen.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pullen|first1=Chas L|title=Magazine of New England History|date=1891|publisher=R. Hammett Tilley|location=New England|pages=58|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=gecNAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA58&dq=chas+l+pullen&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pZckVPb-KsH2yQTr94G4AQ&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=chas%20l%20pullen&f=false|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>
