;1890s
Legal troubles plagued the Pullen family in 1890.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robbing The People|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/28250714/?terms=pullen+robbing+people|accessdate=15 September 2014|publisher=The Times-Picayune (New Orleans, Louisiana)|date=March 13, 1890}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Wrenn|first1=Lynette Boney|title=Crisis and Commission Government in Memphis|date=Mar 1998|publisher=Univ. of Tennessee Press|isbn=9780870499975|pages=32, 61, 124, 158, 226|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=WywV6C0n0QQC&pg=PA32&dq=memphis+board+of+commissioners&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kuMQVOjOONOmyATIu4LwCw&ved=0CDkQ6AEwBQ#v=snippet&q=embezzlement%20pullen&f=false|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> By 1894, Pullen, his father, two brothers, a sister, and their families had moved {{convert|400|mile|km}} south, settling in [[Houma, Louisiana | Houma]] and [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]. In 1895 he was bookkeeping for the Mutual Insurance Company in New Orleans, and his younger brother, Benjamin K. Pullen Jr., was a travel agent.
;1900s
In the 1900 U.S. Census, Pullen, his wife, and 4 daughters are found living in New Orleans.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pullen|first1=Charles|title=United States Census, 1900|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/MS5P-Y56|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> His father died in July of that year; his wife died shortly thereafter in February, 1901.<ref>{{cite web|title=Benjamin King Pullen|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=103458960&ref=acom|website=Find A Grave|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Addie Belle Pullen|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=103459437&ref=acom|website=findagrave.com|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> In 1902, Pullen's eldest daughter, Bessie, married Ernest Johnson and moved to Texas. His younger girls would be cared for by an aunt living in [[Central America]]. His daughter Minnie would marry Texan Joseph Ross, a railroad superintendent, and spend time in Guatemala where their second son was born in 1913. About his life in New Orleans and his budding interest in flowers Powell would say: "I had a little greenhouse in New Orleans before I went to the Canal Zone."<ref name=man>{{cite news|title=Man Who Made Shaw's Garden Orchid Mecca of the World Here to View Collection|publisher=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=September 8, 1926}}</ref>

==New life: country, name, career, passion==
===Also known as (aka) Charles Wesley Powell===
Some combination of events prompted a relatively unconnected Charles L. Pullen to move {{convert|1600|mile|km}} south to Panama. Exactly when and why he reinvented himself as Charles Wesley Powell is a mystery. In a 1928 biography of Powell, some elements of his pre-Panama days are not supported by facts: leading one to wonder why and by whom (probably Powell himself) the details of his life in the U. S. were altered.<ref name=bio /> From 1907<U+2013>1927 he would support himself by working in various positions in a Canal Zone dispensary (basic medical facility) or hospital. With a salary of $60 per month, he started out dispensing [[quinine]] (antimalarial drug) at a labor camp in old Gatun (now covered by 80 feet of rock and earth under Gatun Dam). It is not surprising he would be hired for a position in which precise record keeping was important. To better communicate with patients, he studied Spanish. Soon he was certified as a nurse. The front side of his [https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-1961-40627-11784-79?cc=2193241 <span style="color:#0000FF">employment record</span>]; immigration records in 1913 and 1926 (including addresses in the U.S. of daughter Bessie Johnson and the MBG); and the 1920 U.S. Census (including married daughter Addie in his household) find him using variations of the name Charles Wesley Powell.<ref name=employee /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Charles W.|title=New York, Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/JNRT-V3B|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Charles Wesley|title=New York, New York Passenger and Crew Lists, 1909, 1925-1957|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-1951-21487-21328-64?cc=1923888|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Charles W|title=United States Census, 1920|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/SP8Y-2Z9|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>
;"Pescadore Grande"
"In 1908 Powell transferred to [[Portobelo, Col<U+00F3>n | Porto Bello]] [on the Caribbean Sea] as a dispensary assistant and took up fishing as a hobby, using a row-boat. Early 1910 finds Powell working in a dispensary in [old] Gorgona (now submerged 80 feet below the surface of [[Gatun Lake]]) and fishing in Panama Bay. The local fishermen called him 'Pescadore Grande' (great fisherman). Switching his fishing from Panama Bay to Gatun Lake soon followed."<ref name=bio />

==="Look, Powell&ndash;Oodles of orchids!"===
{{multiple image
| align=right	
| direction =vertical
| width= 200
| image1=Panama canal 1912.jpg
| caption1=Gatun Lake 1912 
| image2=Peristeria elata Orchi 11.jpg
| caption2=Dove orchid	
}}
Gatun Lake, a part of the Panama Canal, was created when the [[U. S. Army Corps of Engineers]] dammed the [[Chagres River | Rio Chagres]] in the early 1900s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gatun Lake|url=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gatun_Lake|website=Wikipedia.org|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> About 1912, Powell and his botanist friend Abel A. Hunter (1877-1936), bought a motor boat for fishing in the newly formed lake.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunter|first1=Abel|title=United States Census, 1900|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-266-11112-154222-77?cc=1325221|website=FamilySearch.org|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunter|first1=Abel Akin|title=United States World War I Draft Registration Cards|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-1971-26447-34726-5?cc=1968530|website=FamilySearch.org|accessdate=2 October 2014}} </ref> "The waters had risen until they presented a surface through which the upper portions of thousands of tall trees protruded. Their craft cut paths between treetops. Hunter exclaimed, 'Look, Powell&ndash;orchids! Oodles of orchids! Treefuls of orchids! Let's get some of 'em.'"<ref name=fish /> "The men knew the dove orchids would soon be submerged by the rising waters of the Chagres River. 
'We were rewarded by a boat-load of the 'El Spirito Santo' or [[Peristeria elata | Holy Ghost Orchid]].' The orchids were brought back to Gorgona and disseminated over the Canal Zone, the United States, and Europe. Soon, the level of the Lake was encroaching on Gorgona, and necessitated a transferring of the workers to [[Balboa]] [Pacific side]."<ref name=bio>{{cite journal|last1=Hunter|first1=A. A.|title=Charles W. Powell|journal=Missouri Botanical Garden bulletin|date=April 1928|volume=XVI|issue=4|pages=53-58|url=https://archive.org/stream/mobot31753002461876#page/18/mode/2up/search/powell|accessdate=18 October 2014}}</ref>

===Powell's orchid garden takes root===
"I can remember my first orchid, I was just looking over the country one Sunday, about 18 months after I got down there [Balboa] when I saw it way up near the top of a tall tree. 'You're certainly a beauty,' I said. 'I must have you.' While I was standing there wondering how on earth to climb that tree a bare-footed Indian came along. 'I'll give you 25 cents gold to get that flower,' I said. The Indian used the vines to swing to the tree [like [[Tarzan]]] and cut off the orchid."<ref name=man /> This acquisition coupled with the memorable experience at Gatun Lake echoing in his mind led to a watershed moment for Powell; "he lost no time starting an orchid garden."<ref name=fish /> "Powell started his collection on his front porch [late 1915]. When that got so packed with plants he couldn't move, he started an annex by building a tier of shelves on the rear wall of his house."<ref name=man /> "It wasn't long until both were overflowing and he had to construct a latticed roof and screened-in, vine-clad, wire mesh walls."<ref name=man /> "The establishing of the garden was actuated by the act of Mrs. A. H. Bryan presenting Mr. Powell with about a thousand plants, and a further donation by Charles H. Beetham."<ref name=bio /> There was nothing published on growing orchids outdoors: Powell ''pioneered'' the techniques. "He studied the orchid intelligently: learning, throughout the years about orchids from books, worldwide correspondence, and visitors."<ref name=fish>{{cite news|title=Fish are forgotten in quest for flowers|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/26508983/|accessdate=14 September 2014|publisher=The Edwardsville Intelligencer|date=June 9, 1936}}</ref> About the books he remarked: "I couldn't read a French or German newspaper, but with a little Latin I could make out the technical works."<ref name=man />

===Flower Power===
{{See also|Orchidelirium}}
References to the power and allure of the wild orchid are peppered throughout the world's cultural, historical, and contemporary beliefs. As far back as the fifth century BC, the Chinese philosopher Confucius used wild orchids as symbolism to deepen the meaning of his poems; "he compared the virtuous man to an orchid. Echoing this thought, Chinese artists sometimes placed orchids in their work to evoke the Confucian qualities of humility, integrity, refinement<U+2014>in fact, all the virtues of a perfectly cultured gentleman and scholar."<ref>{{cite web|title=Orchid Culture Guide|url=http://www.orchidsusa.com/1Introduction.htm|website=Orchidsusa.com|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Orchids: A View From the East|url=http://www.mnh.si.edu/exhibits/orchids/|website=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> "The ancient Greeks associated it with virility, and the Aztecs were said to drink a mixture of the vanilla orchid and chocolate to give them power and strength."<ref>{{cite web|title=History and Meaning of Orchids|url=http://www.proflowers.com/blog/history-and-meaning-of-orchids|website=ProFlowers.com|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> To others, "orchids possess a sensual, quasi-mystical aura: thought of as sexual, wild, rare creatures."<ref name=never /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Ardea|title=The Seductive Orchid|url=http://www.pugetsound.edu/files/resources/11228_Smith.pdf|website=pugetsound.edu|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> In the 1939 book ''The Orchid Hunters'', Norman MacDonald wrote: "For when a man falls in love with orchids, he'll do anything to possess the one he wants. It's like chasing a green-eyed woman [being consumed by desire] or taking cocaine. A sort of madness..."<ref>{{cite book|last1=MacDonald|first1=Norman|title=The Orchid Hunters: A Jungle Adventure|date=1939|publisher=Farrar & Rinehart, Inc.|location=New York|page=1|url=http://books.google.com/books?ei=vm0oVLP0BoSGyASL3YDwCw&id=ATRlAAAAMAAJ&dq=orchid+hunter&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=madness|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> In a 2002 [[Nova (TV series) | ''NOVA'']] interview, [[Susan Orlean]] (Author, [[The Orchid Thief | ''The Orchid Thief'']], non-fiction) revealed her research findings: "Nothing in science can account for the way people feel about orchids. Orchids arouse passion more than romance. They are the sexiest flowers on Earth."<ref name=Orlean>{{cite web|title=Orchid Hunter|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/transcripts/2915_orchid.html|website=NOVA|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>
And in 2006, an article about "Fanatical collectors driving a <U+00A3>6 billion black market of 'trophy' specimens" was published in ''The Telegraph.'' In this article, [[Eric Hansen]] (Author, ''Orchid Fever'', non-fiction) recalls a flower-grower telling him: 'You can get off alcohol, drugs, women, food and cars, but once you're hooked on orchids you're finished. You never get off orchids. Never.'"<ref name=never>{{cite news|title=You can get off alcohol and drugs, but you never get off of orchids. Never|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1508457/You-can-get-off-alcohol-and-drugs-but-you-never-get-off-orchids.-Never.html|accessdate=11 October 2014|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|date=22 January 2006}}</ref> 

Specifically, the prevailing belief about orchids during Powell's lifetime was described thusly: "There is one plant, which stands so far above all the rest for unique beauty and grandeur that it is universally regarded as the aristocrat of the floral kingdom, namely, the orchid. The Central American orchids, above all others in North or South America, are regarded as furnishing the climax [occupying the highest point] and should be called the 'aristocrat of the aristocrats.'"<ref name=moore>{{cite journal|last1=Moore|first1=George, T.|title=Latin America and the queen of flowers|journal=Bulletin of the Pan American Union|date=August 1931|volume=12|pages=1-9|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=oUUzAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA118&dq=powell+orchid+garden+balboa&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZbtFVNroE5aqyATNk4KYDQ&ved=0CFwQ6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q=powell%20orchid%20garden%20balboa&f=false|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>

===Powell the orchid hunter===
{{main|Orchid hunting}}
Falling under the wild orchid's powerful spell, Powell fit the profile of a classic [[orchid hunting | orchid hunter]] with one exception&ndash;he was not interested in selling his treasures&ndash;he wanted to collect them. Some biographical sources indicate Powell collected orchids beginning with his arrival in Panama in 1907; however, is seems more likely his collecting began after he settled in Balboa.<ref>{{cite web|title=JSTOR Global Plants: Powell, Charles W.|url=http://plants.jstor.org/person/bm000036257|website=plants.JSTOR.org|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> At first he collected locally; ultimately, his objective was to "assemble a complete collection of Panama species."<ref name=report /> "Powell and Hunter went on collecting trips in the Chiriqu<U+00ED> region in 1918, 1920, and 1922; Powell went there without Hunter in 1924. Powell's last collecting trip was to the Veraguas Province in March, 1925."<ref name=bio /> In 1931, [[George Thomas Moore | George T. Moore]], director of the MBG wrote: "The perils and experiences of the early orchid hunters were as thrilling and romantic as those of any arctic explorer."<ref name=moore /> About the typical orchid hunter, Susan Orlean had this to say: "[[Orchid hunting]] hasn't really changed over the last 200 years and orchid hunters haven't really changed. You have to be brave; you have to be somewhat foolish."<ref name=Orlean /> 
