{{Quote box
|title =My heart stopped
|tstyle = text-align: left;
|quote =Up in Chiriqu<U+00ED>, in the northwestern corner of Panama, orchids are found in abundance at an altitude of {{convert|4000|ft|m}} to {{convert|6000|ft|m}}. Likewise abundant are barrancas, steep gullies like those in the [[Rocky_Mountains | Rockies]], maybe hundreds of yards (meters) long and {{convert|1000|ft|m}} deep. One day about 6 years ago &ndash; I was 66 then &ndash; I saw a fine plant growing on a half-dead limb that grew out almost horizontally over one of those barrancas. 'I never saw you before,' I thought, and 'I won't let you get away, barranca or no barranca.'  My man shinned out a few feet (roughly a meter) on that dying branch and then scurried back, scared at the prospect of a 500-foot (150 m) fall. That made me mad. I threw off my hat, coat, and shoes and went after that orchid. Just as I reached out for it the branch cracked. My heart stopped. But I never let loose my grip on that plant and scurried back to earth like a scared chipmunk. And that&mdash;that was the first time I ever saw the Odontoglossum Powellia.<ref name=man />
|align =center
|width =95%
|fontsize =90%
|bgcolor =#e6f4d7
}}
{{Quote box
|title =Ants in the plants
|tstyle = text-align: left;
|quote =A colony of vicious ants always is found in the roots of the [[bucket orchid]]. I am beginning to believe the eggs and waste nourish the orchid. As the branch falls [to the ground] the Indian scrambles down [the tree] and dives in the nearest water. You make a noose in a long rope, drop it over the branch and jerk it into the water. In a half hour or so the ants have drowned or floated away. Then you can pick up your rare find, but not before.<ref name=man />
|align =center
|width  =95%
|fontsize =90%
|bgcolor =#e6f4d7
}}
[[George H. Pring]] (see below) elaborated on collecting bucket orchids: "Removing a clump of these plants may be compared with disturbing a hornet's nest, but, according to Mr. Powell, who had experienced both adventures, the hornets are easier to combat than the thousands of small stinging ants."<ref name=bulletin /> Pring then told of a fourth collection technique used by Powell and Hunter; one Pring himself used. "In many instances, to dislodge the epiphyte [an "air plant", ''growing non-parasitically'', sometimes 40-50 feet from the ground] without climbing the tree, it is necessary to cut a sapling with a forked-top as long as the distance up to where it clings. Its roots in some cases are three to four feet long, and great dexterity is required to dislodge it as to not cause injury. During this operation, clouds of dust, granulated bark and moss which rain down from above almost blind the collector."<ref name=bull1927 /> "These men got many fine specimens through this method."<ref name=fish />

==Powell's Horticultural Garden goes global==
===Powell and Rolfe===
{{Auto images
|title= Found in Powell's garden
|align=right
|total_width =200
|text_align=center
|image1=A and B Larsen orchids - Epidendrum fragrans DSCN7786.JPG
|width1 =460
|height1 =600
|caption1=Epidendrum fragrans
|image2=Vanilla planifolia 02.JPG
|width2=460
|height2=600
|caption2=Vanilla on trellises
}}
As his garden expanded over the years, Powell's orchid documentation, and jungle explorations took a new path. Pursuit, care, and documenting his beloved orchids occupied most of his spare time. "Although 193 [now 195] of Powell<U+2019>s [[specimens]] were recorded without dates; the first dated records of collections began in 1915. In early 1918, realizing that many of his plants were not described in his books, he made contact with [[Robert Allen Rolfe | R. Allen Rolfe]] at the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, England."<ref name=lank /> A package C. W. P. (Powell) sent Rolfe was acknowledged by the latter via ''The Orchid Review'' (May 1918): "The package duly arrived, but was badly broken and the contents missing. Perhaps further materials can be sent. In practice we find the most successful method is to press small specimens in a fold of blotting paper and enclose in an ordinary letter."<ref name=review>{{cite journal|last1=Rolfe|first1=R. Allen|title=Answers to Correspondents/Orchids of Panama|journal=The Orchid Review|date=May 1918|volume=xxvi|page=120, 180|url=http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/114453#page/142/mode/1up|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=CZreport>{{cite web|title=Annual Report of the Canal Zone Experiment Gardens, 1939|url=https://archive.org/stream/annual39cana/annual39cana_djvu.txt|website=archive.org|publisher=The Panama Canal Press Mount Hops, C. Z.|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref>

;Herbarium specimen preparation
{{See also|Herbarium}}
Transitioning from hobbyist to horticulturist, Powell needed a way to forward his finds to researchers and preserve them for future reference. He studied the standardized method for [[specimen]] preservation and storage. Specimens were typically preserved by extracting moisture in a device called a plant press. Although he was initially cautioned against it, he added artificial heat (an electric iron) which aided in the quality of the results in the tropics.<ref name=report /><ref name=bulletin>{{cite web|title=Missouri Botanical Garden bulletin|url=http://archive.org/stream/mobot31753002461801/mobot31753002461801_djvu.txt|website=archive.org|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref> The pressed plant could then be affixed to a mounting sheet (11 X 17 inch paper). Label data (essential documentary information) was added. Once label data was added to the mounting sheet, it was ready for shipping. The mounting sheet (specimen) became a candidate for long-term storage in a repository (like the [[Harvard University Herbaria]]). Once accepted, the mounting sheet would then be known as a [[herbarium]] specimen. At first he sent just the preserved flowers, but soon he was asked to send preserved plants that included the roots, stems, leaves, flowers, and seeds. Powell painstakingly crafted his mounting sheets; he enhanced them with fieldnotes, illustrations, flower cutouts, and photographs. His original sheets would stand on their own as works of art; over time they have evolved into beautiful, remarkably detailed documents.
[[File:Brassia caudata 2.JPG|thumb|Brassia caudata/Spider orchid<br />is also found in [[Florida]], U.S.]]
;Herbarium specimen examples
Over 100 examples of Powell's collection records, many with ''images'' of his herbarium specimens, are found in a virtual herbarium at the [http://kiki.huh.harvard.edu/databases/specimen_search.php?start=1&cltr=C.%20W.%20Powell <span style="color:#0000FF">Harvard University Herbaria and Libraries.</span>]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=C. W.|title=Index of Botanical Specimens|url=http://kiki.huh.harvard.edu/databases/specimen_search.php?start=1&cltr=C.%20W.%20Powell|website=Harvard University Herbaria & Library|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>

For his spider orchid ([[Brassia caudata |''Brassia caudata'']]) [http://www.tropicos.org/image/8760 <span style="color:#0000FF">with cutout.</span>]<ref>{{cite web|title=Powell - 72 - Panama|url=http://www.tropicos.org/image/8760|website=Tropicos|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>

For his ''Prosthechea fragrans'' (Sw.) W.E. Higgins showing the [http://www.tropicos.org/image/28960 <span style="color:#0000FF">evolution of a herbarium specimen.</span>]<ref>{{cite web|title=Powell - 208 - Panama|url=http://www.tropicos.org/image/28960|website=Tropicos|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>

;Herbarium specimen examples with hand-drawn illustrations
Powell's signature, [http://ids.lib.harvard.edu/ids/view/5864550 <span style="color:#0000FF">CWP.</span>] (CW is overlapping), is found in the lower right.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Charles W.|title=Index of Botanists|url=http://ids.lib.harvard.edu/ids/view/5864550|website=Harvard|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>

''Epidendrum fragrans'' enhanced with Powell's [http://ids.lib.harvard.edu/ids/view/5832270 <span style="color:#0000FF">flower-only drawing</span>]<ref name=draw>{{cite web|title=Epidendrum fragans|url=http://ids.lib.harvard.edu/ids/view/5832270|website=Harvard University Herbaria and Libraries|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>

;Information included in Powell's label data and fieldnotes
{{columns-list|2|
* Scientific name: genus and species
* Detailed location: country of collection (example: Repub of Panama/Province of Chiriqu<U+00ED>); locality (examples: Foot hills east of the city or Cativa-Porto Bello trail); [[altitude]] (examples: sea level or 4-5000Ft)
* Habitat (examples: grows in ants nests or grows in shady places); plant<U+2019>s position on a tree (example: laying flat on the tree limb)
* Plant's description: color and details of the flower (example: dark blood red); color and texture of the leaves (example: dark, velvety green)
* time of year or month range it flowered (example: July to August)
* Collector's name: C. W. Powell
* Determiner's name
* Collection number
* Date of collection
}}

In July, 1918, Powell sent Rolfe a series of herbarium specimens. It took roughly 8 months for a portion (29) to be determined, communication slowed; Rolfe was in ill health and died before he had a chance to [fully] study Powell<U+2019>s collection.<ref name=review1919>{{cite journal|last1=Rolfe|first1=R. Allen|title=Answers to Correspondents|journal=The Orchid Review|date=March 1919|volume=xxvii|page=68|url=http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/114158#page/85/mode/1up|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=lank /> Rolfe's death was a great disappointment to Powell; he had derived much encouragement and help from Rolfe's kindly cooperation and guidance."<ref name=report />

;"Parasita Grande"
Accustomed to dogged pursuit in genealogy research, Powell pressed on. He realized the need to ''systematically'' document the "Orchids of Panama" for study.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dressler|first1=Robert L.|title=Field Guide to the Orchids of Costa Rica and Panama|date=1993|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801481390|page=14|page=14|edition=l|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=LiMbwG0pALkC&pg=PA14&dq=c+w+powell+orchid&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9XITVPa4Gc-lyASil4HwCg&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=c%20w%20powell%20orchid&f=false}}</ref> He was energized by the thrill of the hunt. His fellow researchers began to take notice. Powell was persistent, he infused enthusiasm in his dealings, and he instilled in his fellow researchers the confidence that&mdash;he had something to offer in the confusing world of the [[Orchidaceae]]. "Mr. Powell's enthusiasm for these plants has caused him to be locally termed 'the Orchid Man' ('Parasita Grande'), and his garden is one of the show places in Balboa to both the botanist and tourist."<ref name=bulletin /> Perhaps while acting as tour guide, the idea&ndash;to someday donate his garden&ndash;sprouted; little did he know how much joy and peaceful beauty his expanding orchid collection would one day bring to visitors of a botanical garden {{convert|2300|mile|km}} away. The reputation of Powell's Horticultural Garden, Balboa, Canal Zone began to grow on a global scale.

===Images of Powell and his Canal Zone garden===
[[File:Annualreportofbo1924smit 0461a.jpg|thumb|Exterior garden view. Powell on left, dressed in white, for scale]]
"Orchids are surprisingly difficult to see in the wild; the majority being epiphytic, growing high in the canopy on trunks, branches or in crotches out of sight."<ref>{{cite web|title=Costa Rica Guide|url=http://costa-rica-guide.com/travel/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=189&Itemid=347|website=Lankester Botanical Gardens|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref> In Powell's garden they were at eye-level&mdash;a sight to behold. "A rustic gate gives entrance to this miniature paradise. The gate posts are formed of dead jungle trees covered with Orchids. The walks, bordered with beautiful ferns and lilies, lead between Orchid-covered dead trees that are a riot of colour."<ref name=review /> "Much painstaking labor has converted it into a miniature jungle&mdash;plus all the beauty and minus all the dangers of a real jungle. There are few thrills equal to seeing in the early morning a host of these beautiful flowers that have suddenly burst in full blossom, nodding a merry good morning."<ref name=union />

Six images are hosted in an online exhibit by Missouri Digital Heritage: contributions by [[Missouri Botanical Garden]].
