}}
===Associations with world's leading authorities===
The relationships between the orchid experts of the time were complicated; mutual respect, admiration, cooperation and financial support of each other were interwoven with intense competition, rivalry, and double-dealing.<ref name=lank />
;Powell and Schlechter
Beginning in 1919, thanks to a tip from a correspondent in [[Costa Rica]], German botanist [[Rudolf Schlechter]] (curator of the herbarium at the Berlin Botanical Garden) began corresponding with and receiving numerous duplicate specimens (ones originally sent to Rolfe) from Powell. "Schlechter immediately recognized the importance of the plant collection, and encouraged Mr. Powell in every way to send in further specimens."<ref name=CZreport /> "Schlechter took up the [[Taxonomy (biology) | taxonomy]] (classification) of Panamanian orchids in August, 1920."<ref name=bio /> "An astonishing number of plants proved to be entirely new to science (not less than 75)."<ref name=CZreport /><ref name=bulletin /> Schlechter added: "Just as important as the new species is the rediscovery of a whole series of species, having originally been discovered by [[J<U+00F3>zef Warszewicz | Warszewicz]], but never found again."<ref name=sch /> "Schlechter wrote to Powell: 'Your exploration of the orchid flora of Panama is one of the most important facts in orchidology during the later years.'<U+201D><ref name=lank /> Schlechter named dozens of species in Powell's honor (see Schlechter's author abbreviation, Schltr., in "Legacy" below). Waiting until after Rolfe's death (1921), in 1922, Schlechter published his 95 page ''Orchidaceae Powellianae Panamenses'' (collections by C. Powell) part of which transcribes as follows: "It is sure that no one has made such a contribution to our knowledge of these orchids as Mr. Powell through his 'exceedingly mighty collection,' which contains not only species with conspicuous flowers, but also those in which the size of the blooms scarcely exceeds that of a pin-head."<ref name=sch>{{cite book|last1=Schlechter|first1=Rudolf|title=Orchidaceae Powellianae Panamenses|date=1922|publisher=Verlag des Repertoriums|location=Germany}}</ref><ref name=bulletin /> "We cannot thank Mr. Powell enough for this self-sacrificing research that he has undertaken in spite of his age. For the orchidology of Panama he has done more than any of his predecessors."<ref name=bulletin /> Most of Schlechter's specimens were destroyed in 1943, during the bombing of Berlin, in the Second World War.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oakes Ames Orchid Herbarium|url=http://huh.harvard.edu/pages/oakes-ames-orchid-herbarium-ames|website=Harvard University Herbaria and Library|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ignatz_Urban]</ref>

;Powell, Oakes Ames, and Blanche Ames
In 1922, Powell began relations with Harvard University<U+2019>s [[Oakes Ames_(botanist) | Oakes Ames]], a botanist, and the most eminent American orchid authority at the time. Due to intense competition with Schlechter, "Ames went so far as to sign with Powell a formal contract in which the latter would collect orchids for him for U.S. $100 per month. From that point forward, Powell only sent Schlechter duplicate specimens. Ames met Powell in Panama in 1923. That same year, Ames praised the quality of Powell<U+2019>s work: 'His indefatigable zeal is one of the joys in my contemplation of Central American orchidology. His specimens are often works of art.'<U+201D><ref name=lank /> Based on an orchid from Powell's garden, Ames' wife, [[Blanche Ames Ames]], recognized as an outstanding botanical illustrator, enriched one of her husband's specimens by painting this [http://ids.lib.harvard.edu/ids/view/5843737 <span style="color:#0000FF">watercolor</span>]. Today, the Economic Herbarium of Oakes Ames at Harvard University has a searchable specimen database which includes many of Powell's original works.<ref>{{cite web|title=Econonic Herbarium of Oakes Ames|url=http://huh.harvard.edu/pages/economic-herbarium-oakes-ames-econ|website=Harvard University Herbaria and Libraries|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>

;Powell and Lankester
In September of 1922, Powell sent a letter to Ames introducing "my good friend" [[:es:Charles H. Lankester]]. Lankester, a British coffee grower, naturalist, and orchidologist, was living in [[Cartago, Costa Rica]], a country with great potential for new to science orchid species. Powell facilitated what would become a "deep friendship between Lankester and Ames that lasted 25 years."<ref name=lank /> Traveling to Costa Rica in 1925, Powell visited Lankester, who in turn traveled to Panama in 1927. <U+201C>I have just spent a fortnight with my fellow sufferer from orchiditis, CWP, + it was a very delightful time of talk and talk and then talk.<U+201D><ref name=lank /> Lankester's orchid garden transformed over time into the [[Lankester Botanical Garden | Lankester Botanical Gardens]]. Located outside of Cartago, Costa Rica, the garden is operated by the University of Costa Rica as a research center.<ref>[[Lankester Botanical Garden]]</ref>

;Powell and Standley
{{Quote box
|title =Standley's summation
|quote =There can scarcely be for any tropical country a record of one person who has contributed so much to the knowledge of the orchid flora. The Powell orchid garden at Balboa is one of the most interesting sights of the Canal Zone, and botanically by far the most remarkable thing to be seen there. It is something unique in tropical America, if not in the whole world.<ref name=report>{{cite journal|title=Annual Report to the Board of Regents of the Smithsonian Institution|date=1924|pages=358-379|url=https://archive.org/details/annualreportofbo1924smit|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>
|align  = right
|width =22%
|fontsize =95%
|bgcolor =#e0eeee
|qalign =left
}}
In the 1924 Annual Report to the Board of Regents of [[The Smithsonian Institution]], [[Paul Carpenter Standley | Paul C. Standley]] reported about Powell: "Years of experience, through which the best methods have been discovered, combined with the attention to details such as other collectors rarely attain, have enabled him to make specimens which are unsurpassed. Among the vines that cover the trellises in the Powell garden are various plants of Vanilla, of which there are two common species in Panama, V. ''planifolia'' with narrow leaves (see image above) and V. ''pompona'' with wide leaves."<ref name=report />

;Powell and Pring
George H. Pring, a horticulturist at the MBG, made many trips to remote locations in Central and South America.<ref>{{cite web|title=George Henry Pring|url=http://www.kewguild.org.uk/media/pdfs/v6s56p825-3.pdf|website=kewguild.org.uk|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> "In 1923 Pring visited the Panama Canal Zone, where he spent six months, weeks of which were at Powell's garden talking orchids from 6 a.m. to 3 a.m."<ref name=man /> "Powell, in turn, was overjoyed to entertain a man who knew orchids from the outside in."<ref name=fish /> Pring presented Powell with rare plants gathered in the [[Andes]] and Powell reciprocated with 300 plants from his garden for the MBG.<ref>{{cite news|title=Plant gift, by Powell of Balboa|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/1683012/|accessdate=15 October 2014|publisher=The Neosho Daily News|date=25 March 1926}}</ref> This association would prove mutually beneficial; back at the MBG, "a great interest arose for Panama<U+2019>s orchids."<ref name=lank /> In 1926, Powell and Pring would be together again: this time in Missouri. "They appeared to take up the conversation where they left off three years ago. Long botanical names crackled in their dialogue."<ref name=man />

==1926==
===Donation===
[[File:Annualreportofbo1924smit 0461.jpg|thumb|7,000 plants-500 orchid species]]
Knowing the time would come when he could no longer care for the 7,000 plants (including palms, ferns, and roughly 500 orchid species) in his astonishing garden, "On March 1, 1926, Powell, Pring, and George Moore (Director of the MBG-aka Shaw's Garden) met in Panama and finalized the details of a great gift&mdash;Powell generously presented the Missouri Botanical Garden with his world-wide-known collection of orchids."<ref name=bull1927>{{cite journal|title=Thirty-Eighth report of the director|journal=Missouri Botanical Garden Bulletin|date=1927|volume=XV|issue=1|pages=5-6|url=https://archive.org/stream/mobot31753003136998#page/n3/mode/2up|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=CZreport /><ref name=bio /> "For the benefit of orchid growers throughout the world," the MBG's 1926 bulletin gives an accounting of some the [https://archive.org/stream/mobot31753002461850#page/103/mode/2up <span style="color:#0000FF">orchids gifted by Powell.</span>] "At age 72, Powell had one of the greatest private orchid collections in the world; his donation made the Shaw's Garden orchid collection the finest in the world."<ref name=bull1927 /><ref name=man />

===Creation of Panama Extension Station===
"The MBG created a <U+2018>tropical station<U+2019> at the foot of [[Ancon Hill]] (hill overlooking Panama City, Panama), on lands [{{convert|2.5|acre|ha}}] granted by the Canal Zone Government. Then Secretary of War and former Park Commissioner of St. Louis, Missouri, [[Dwight F. Davis]], approved the MBG's application for this land grant."<ref name=fish /> "Powell's collection became the [nucleus of the] Panama Extension Station of the MBG; he was appointed its first director and a residence was built for him on the grounds."<ref>{{cite web|title=An Illustrated History of the Missouri Botanical Garden 1920s|url=http://www.mobot.org/mobot/archives/section.asp?section=34|website=Missouri Botanical Garden|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=CZreport /> "Powell<U+2019>s collection marked the beginning of the Garden<U+2019>s reputation in orchid horticulture."<ref name=lank /> "After Powell<U+2019>s death there was a good deal of confusion regarding the care of the plants; they were neglected and many died. Pring and Hunter spent two months restocking the grounds. Hunter took over the direction of the Tropical Station and maintained this position until his own death in 1936. In 1939, the Tropical Station was transferred to the Canal Zone Government. During its almost 13 years of existence, the Tropical Station supplied the greenhouses in Saint Louis with a constant flow of living plants."<ref name=lank /> "Today, Ancon Hill is a popular jogging and hiking trek. All manner of vegetation and birds can be seen, including a large number of orchids (which are protected by [[CITES]])."<ref>{{cite web|title=Ancon Hill|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancon_Hill|website=Wikipedia.org|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>
===Powell visits Missouri Botanical Garden===
On August 30, 1926, Powell travelled from Panama to the United States on the [[SS Ancon | SS ''Ancon'']], an American steamship and the first ship to officially transit the Panama Canal in 1914. "He met, sometimes for the first time, his 'Brothers in Science.' Visits to [[New York City | New York]], [[Philadelphia]] and [[Washington, DC | Washington]] preceded his arrival in [[St. Louis, Missouri]]. Everywhere he was greeted as an old friend by scientists and orchid enthusiasts. These knew him through a decade of learned correspondence and others had made pilgrimages to his famous garden for it is a mecca of the orchid world."<ref name=man /> After spending more than 10 years searching the tropical jungles of Panama, he was lionized as "The Canal Zone's exotic plant specialist."
===Recognition and retirement===
Charles W. Powell was awarded the [[Roosevelt Medal]] with two service bars (second bar awarded on March 1, 1913) for continuous distinguished civilian work as an employee of the Isthmian Canal Commission (or the Panama Railroad Company). Of roughly 50,000 workers, only 1,661 medalists earned the second bar.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Canal Medal List|journal=Panama Canal Record|date=August 27, 1913|volume=VII|issue=35|page=332|url=http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00097368/00007/356x?search=powell&vo=11|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Roosevelt Medal with Two Bars|url=http://www.coins-of-panama.com/canalmedals/cm10-2.html|website=Coins-of-Panama.com|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref>

Retiring on October 10, 1926, Powell's service record in the Canal Zone's Sanitation department documents his [https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-1961-40627-11853-73?cc=2193241 <span style="color:#0000FF">annuity.</span>]<ref>{{cite web|title=United States, Panama Canal Sailing Lists, 1905-1937|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.3.1/TH-1961-40627-11853-73?cc=2193241|website=Family Search|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref>

===''Desiderata'': "The answer was orchids"===
[[File:Sobralia decora - Flickr 003.jpg|thumb|right|Sobraila decora. See Powell's specimen [http://ids.lib.harvard.edu/ids/view/5284217 <span style="color:#0000FF">February 1915</span>]<ref>{{cite web|title=Sobralia decora|url=http://ids.lib.harvard.edu/ids/view/5284217|website=Harvard University Herbaria and Libraries|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>]]
Life in early 1900s Panama presented a unique opportunity for Powell to find his passion in orchids. The labor requirement for the construction of the Panama Canal provided him with a livelihood; and an outing on the newly created Gatun Lake awakened a desire to "catch" orchids instead of fish.<ref name=fish /> Soon, he would become a man with a mission: a man with direction and purpose. Powell searched high and low for beautiful, rare and new-to-science orchids with great vigor. He risked life and limb to acquire his specimens. The worldwide correspondence, camaraderie, conversation and competition among like-minded orchid lovers suited his nature. What started out as a hobby, earned him a global identity. Powell's orchid garden was the culmination of his later life's efforts: the essence of a late bloomer. Charles Wesley Powell's donation was the manifestation of his calling to serve mankind by contributing to the greater common good. 

''Desiderata'' (Latin: "desired things"):
{{cquote|'''I wanted flowers. Naturally I wanted the best;'''

'''naturally I wanted something I had never seen.'''

'''The answer was orchids.'''<ref name=man /> &mdash;Powell, 1926
 }}
==Death==
"Charles Wesley Powell's health failed him at the very beginning of the peaceful and interesting years which he had planned. He died of heart disease, very suddenly, on August 18, 1927, at the age of 73."<ref name=CZreport /><ref name=expert /> Three daughters survived him. He and his daughter, Addie (n<U+00E9>e Pullen) Foster (1887-1925), were buried in the [[Corozal American Cemetery and Memorial]] in Panama.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Charles Wesley|title=Burial|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=powell&GSiman=1&GScid=1990854&GRid=38878234&|website=findagrave.com|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Foster|first1=Addie|title=Burial|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=38151547&ref=acom|website=findagrave.com|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>

==Legacy: Orchids named in Powell's honor==
{{See also|Taxonomy of the Orchidaceae}}
"The Orchid family ([[Orchidaceae]]) contains the largest number of plant species in the world - up to 30,000. Panama alone has about 1,100 known species."<ref name=new>{{cite web|title=Lophiaris silverarum: New Species of Orchid Discovered in Panama|url=http://www.sci-news.com/biology/science-lophiaris-silverarum-new-species-orchid-panama-01862.html|website=Sci-News.com|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Internet Orchid Species Encyclopedia|url=http://www.orchidspecies.com/index.htm|website=orchidspecies.com|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> Powell collected at least 380 distinct specimens.<ref>{{cite web|title=C. W. Powell|url=http://kiki.huh.harvard.edu/databases/specimen_search.php?start=1&cltr=C.%20W.%20Powell|website=Harvard University Herbaria and Libraries|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>

<U+201C>Orchids are a difficult and confusing [[taxonomic group]]. People who specialize in the Orchid family usually spend years naming different species based on DNA and morphology."<ref name=new />

